{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, integrating DL tools into traditional paleontological practices is not straightforward, given the rich history of domain-specific expertise and methodologies in paleontology.",
    "Merging conventional practices with DL requires careful consideration to ensure DL models complement and incorporate, rather than overshadow the crucial insights provided by experienced paleontologists (Fischer et al. 2018; Lamichhaney et al. 2019).",
    "Moreover, challenges arise from the varying levels of specificity employed by paleontologists when describing and classifying fossils.",
    "Practitioners are often divided into 'lumpers' and 'splitters,' with lumpers tending to group fossils into fewer species and splitters advocating for the recognition of more species from the same fossil data.",
    "These discrepancies in classification approaches could pose significant challenges for automated processes, which may struggle to reconcile the diverse taxonomic interpretations when integrating multiple studies."
  ]
}